msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:54
msgid "Anatomy of a kernel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:56
msgid ""
"Here's a vector addition with a twist: the element-wise addition is factored "
"out into a plain helper function. Both the kernel and the helper live in the "
"same file alongside host code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:58
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{cuda_module, kernel, thread, DisjointSlice};\n"
"use cuda_core::{CudaContext, DeviceBuffer, LaunchConfig};\n"
"\n"
"/// Plain helper function -- no annotation needed.\n"
"/// The compiler discovers it automatically because `vecadd` calls it.\n"
"fn add(a: f32, b: f32) -> f32 {\n"
"    a + b\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[cuda_module]\n"
"mod kernels {\n"
"    use super::*;\n"
"\n"
"    #[kernel]\n"
"    pub fn vecadd(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"        let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"        let i = idx.get();\n"
"        if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"            *c_elem = add(a[i], b[i]);\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"fn main() {\n"
"    let ctx = CudaContext::new(0).unwrap();\n"
"    let stream = ctx.default_stream();\n"
"\n"
"    const N: usize = 1024;\n"
"    let a_host: Vec<f32> = (0..N).map(|i| i as f32).collect();\n"
"    let b_host: Vec<f32> = (0..N).map(|i| (i * 2) as f32).collect();\n"
"\n"
"    let a_dev = DeviceBuffer::from_host(&stream, &a_host).unwrap();\n"
"    let b_dev = DeviceBuffer::from_host(&stream, &b_host).unwrap();\n"
"    let mut c_dev = DeviceBuffer::<f32>::zeroed(&stream, N).unwrap();\n"
"\n"
"    let module = kernels::load(&ctx).expect(\"Failed to load embedded "
"module\");\n"
"    // SAFETY: `for_num_elems` is 1D and all three buffers contain N "
"elements.\n"
"    unsafe {\n"
"        module.vecadd(\n"
"            &stream,\n"
"            LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32),\n"
"            &a_dev,\n"
"            &b_dev,\n"
"            &mut c_dev,\n"
"        )\n"
"    }\n"
"    .unwrap();\n"
"\n"
"    let c_host = c_dev.to_host_vec(&stream).unwrap();\n"
"    let errors = (0..N)\n"
"        .filter(|&i| (c_host[i] - (a_host[i] + b_host[i])).abs() > 1e-5)\n"
"        .count();\n"
"\n"
"    if errors == 0 {\n"
"        println!(\"PASSED: all {} elements correct\", N);\n"
"    } else {\n"
"        eprintln!(\"FAILED: {} errors\", errors);\n"
"        std::process::exit(1);\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:121
msgid "There's a lot happening here. Let's unpack the key pieces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:123
msgid "Single-source compilation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:125
msgid ""
"The kernel and host code live in **the same file** and are compiled with a "
"single `cargo` command invocation. The codegen backend intercepts "
"compilation, routes `#[kernel]` functions through the MIR-to-PTX pipeline, "
"and delegates everything else to standard LLVM. The final binary contains "
"native host code plus the embedded device artifact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:127
msgid "`#[kernel]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:129
msgid ""
"Marks a function as a **launchable kernel entry point** -- the GPU "
"equivalent of `main`. The function is compiled to PTX via the pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:131
msgid "Rust source → MIR → Pliron IR → LLVM IR → PTX\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:135
msgid ""
"The same function is also visible to the host compiler for type-checking, "
"but its body is never called on the CPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:137
msgid "Device functions (auto-discovery)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:139
msgid ""
"The `add` helper above has **no annotation**. When the compiler processes a "
"`#[kernel]`, it walks the call graph and automatically discovers every "
"function the kernel calls. Those functions are compiled to PTX as device "
"functions and inlined by the backend -- you don't need to mark them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:142
msgid ""
"The `#[device]` attribute exists but serves a different purpose: it marks a "
"function as a standalone device compilation root (for building Rust device "
"libraries consumed by C++) or is used in `#[device] extern \"C\" { ... }` "
"blocks to declare external device functions for FFI with CUDA C++ LTOIR. You "
"do **not** need `#[device]` for private helper functions called from a "
"kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:145
msgid "`#[cuda_module]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:147
msgid ""
"`#[cuda_module]` wraps the inline kernel module and generates a typed host "
"API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:149
msgid ""
"let module = kernels::load(&ctx)?;\n"
"// SAFETY: this is a 1D launch and all three buffers contain N elements.\n"
"unsafe {\n"
"    module.vecadd(\n"
"        &stream,\n"
"        LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32),\n"
"        &a_dev,\n"
"        &b_dev,\n"
"        &mut c_dev,\n"
"    )\n"
"}?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:163
msgid ""
"The loader reads the embedded device artifact from the host binary, caches "
"kernel function handles, and exposes each `#[kernel]` as a Rust method. The "
"method signature mirrors the kernel signature, with device slices mapped to "
"`DeviceBuffer` borrows. This checks argument types, but a raw `LaunchConfig` "
"does not prove that a 1D-index kernel was given a 1D launch. Raw generated "
"launch methods are therefore unsafe. A declared launch contract enables the "
"safe prepared path shown in [Launching Kernels](../gpu-programming/launching-"
"kernels.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:171
msgid ""
"`load_kernel_module` and `cuda_launch!` remain available as lower-level APIs "
"for manual sidecar artifact loading and custom launch code. `cuda_launch!` "
"cannot check arguments against the kernel signature, so it is unsafe and "
"must be wrapped in `unsafe { }`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:176
msgid "Argument scalarization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:178
msgid ""
"Slices cross the host/device ABI as their `(ptr, len)` components -- the "
"host passes them as two kernel arguments, and the device compiler "
"reassembles the slice in the entry block. Structs and closures by value "
"travel as one byval `.param` instead, so the host packet pushes the whole "
"aggregate as a single slot (this matches what the launcher actually does and "
"avoids mismatches with field-by-field declarations). All of this is fully "
"transparent -- the kernel signature still looks like ordinary Rust:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:180
msgid ""
"Host:   unsafe { module.vecadd(&stream, raw_config, &data, ...) }\n"
"          → extracts (ptr, len) for the slice, passes two args\n"
"\n"
"PTX:    .entry kernel(.param .u64 ptr, .param .u64 len, ...)\n"
"          → receives flat slice parameters\n"
"\n"
"Device: kernel body sees unified &[T] slice\n"
"          → compiler reconstructs at entry\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:191
msgid "Dynamic struct layout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:193
msgid ""
"When you pass structs to the GPU, cuda-oxide queries rustc for the **exact "
"byte offsets** of each field and rebuilds the layout with explicit padding "
"on the device side. This means `#[repr(C)]` is **not required** -- regular "
"Rust structs work as-is, even across HMM (GPU direct access to host memory)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:197
msgid "Going async"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:199
msgid ""
"For multi-kernel pipelines or concurrent workloads, cuda-oxide provides an "
"async execution model built on Tokio. Let's scaffold an async project and "
"walk through the differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:201
msgid "Create an async project"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:203
msgid ""
"cargo oxide new my_async_kernel --async\n"
"cd my_async_kernel\n"
"cargo oxide run\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:209
msgid ""
"The `--async` flag generates a project with `tokio` and `cuda-async` "
"dependencies pre-configured."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:211
msgid "Full example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:213
msgid ""
"Here's the generated async vecadd template (with minor formatting edits for "
"readability):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:215
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{cuda_module, kernel, thread, DisjointSlice};\n"
"use cuda_async::device_context::init_device_contexts;\n"
"use cuda_async::device_operation::DeviceOperation;\n"
"use cuda_core::LaunchConfig;\n"
"\n"
"#[cuda_module]\n"
"mod kernels {\n"
"    use super::*;\n"
"\n"
"    #[kernel]\n"
"    pub fn vecadd(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"        let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"        let i = idx.get();\n"
"        if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"            *c_elem = a[i] + b[i];\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[tokio::main]\n"
"async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\n"
"    use cuda_async::device_box::DeviceBox;\n"
"    use cuda_core::memory::{malloc_async, memcpy_dtoh_async, "
"memcpy_htod_async};\n"
"    use std::mem;\n"
"\n"
"    // 1. Initialize the device context map (default device 0, 1 device).\n"
"    //    The round-robin stream pool is created lazily on first use.\n"
"    init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
"\n"
"    // 2. Load the embedded kernel module from the async device context.\n"
"    let module = kernels::load_async(0)?;\n"
"\n"
"    const N: usize = 1024;\n"
"    let a_host: Vec<f32> = (0..N).map(|i| i as f32).collect();\n"
"    let b_host: Vec<f32> = (0..N).map(|i| (i * 2) as f32).collect();\n"
"\n"
"    // 3. Allocate device memory and copy host data.\n"
"    let (a_dev, b_dev, mut c_dev) =\n"
"        cuda_async::device_context::with_cuda_context(0, |ctx| {\n"
"            let stream = ctx.default_stream();\n"
"            let bytes = N * mem::size_of::<f32>();\n"
"            unsafe {\n"
"                let a = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), bytes).unwrap();\n"
"                let b = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), bytes).unwrap();\n"
"                let c = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), bytes).unwrap();\n"
"                memcpy_htod_async(a, a_host.as_ptr(), bytes, stream."
"cu_stream()).unwrap();\n"
"                memcpy_htod_async(b, b_host.as_ptr(), bytes, stream."
"cu_stream()).unwrap();\n"
"                stream.synchronize().unwrap();\n"
"                (\n"
"                    DeviceBox::<[f32]>::from_raw_parts(a, N, 0),\n"
"                    DeviceBox::<[f32]>::from_raw_parts(b, N, 0),\n"
"                    DeviceBox::<[f32]>::from_raw_parts(c, N, 0),\n"
"                )\n"
"            }\n"
"        })?;\n"
"\n"
"    // 4. Launch -- returns a lazy DeviceOperation, no GPU work yet.\n"
"    // SAFETY: this is 1D, buffers contain N elements, and module/scheduler\n"
"    // both use device 0's context.\n"
"    unsafe {\n"
"        module.vecadd_async(\n"
"            LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32),\n"
"            &a_dev,\n"
"            &b_dev,\n"
"            &mut c_dev,\n"
"        )\n"
"    }?\n"
"    .sync()?;  // Block until the GPU finishes.\n"
"\n"
"    // 5. Copy results back to host.\n"
"    let mut c_host = vec![0.0f32; N];\n"
"    cuda_async::device_context::with_cuda_context(0, |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.default_stream();\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            memcpy_dtoh_async(\n"
"                c_host.as_mut_ptr(),\n"
"                c_dev.cu_deviceptr(),\n"
"                N * mem::size_of::<f32>(),\n"
"                stream.cu_stream(),\n"
"            )\n"
"            .unwrap();\n"
"            stream.synchronize().unwrap();\n"
"        }\n"
"    })?;\n"
"\n"
"    // 6. Verify.\n"
"    let errors = (0..N)\n"
"        .filter(|&i| (c_host[i] - (a_host[i] + b_host[i])).abs() > 1e-5)\n"
"        .count();\n"
"\n"
"    if errors == 0 {\n"
"        println!(\"PASSED: all {} elements correct\", N);\n"
"    } else {\n"
"        eprintln!(\"FAILED: {} errors\", errors);\n"
"        std::process::exit(1);\n"
"    }\n"
"\n"
"    Ok(())\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:317
msgid "What changed from sync"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:319
msgid ""
"The kernel itself is **identical** -- async only changes how you launch and "
"manage GPU work on the host side."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:321
msgid "`{kernel}_async` instead of `{kernel}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:322
msgid ""
"Returns a lazy `DeviceOperation` rather than launching immediately. No GPU "
"work happens until you explicitly schedule it. This lets you build a "
"computation graph before committing resources."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:324
msgid "`init_device_contexts(default_device, num_devices)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:325
msgid ""
"Initializes the thread-local device context map, setting the default GPU "
"ordinal and capacity for multi-device use. The round-robin stream pool is "
"created lazily on first use. Operations are then assigned to streams in "
"round-robin order, maximizing GPU occupancy without manual stream management."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:327
msgid "`DeviceBox` instead of `DeviceBuffer`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:328
msgid ""
"Async-safe wrapper for device memory. Works with the stream pool and "
"supports async allocation via `malloc_async`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:330
msgid "`.sync()` vs `.await`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:331
msgid ""
"`.sync()` blocks the calling thread until the GPU finishes -- use it when "
"you have nothing else to do on the host. `.await` suspends the current Tokio "
"task and lets other tasks progress while waiting -- use it when you have "
"concurrent host work or multiple GPU pipelines in flight."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:333
msgid "`and_then` / `zip!`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:334
msgid ""
"Chain dependent operations with `.and_then(|result| next_op)`. Run "
"independent operations concurrently with `zip!(op_a, op_b)` -- both are "
"submitted to the stream pool, and the combined result is available when both "
"complete. These combinators let you express complex multi-kernel pipelines "
"declaratively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../getting-started/hello-gpu.md:337
msgid ""
"For a more complete async example, see `async_mlp` -- a multi-kernel forward "
"pass (GEMM, MatVec, ReLU) with `and_then` chaining, `zip!` for parallel "
"allocation, and `Arc`-shared weights across concurrent batches. Run it with "
"`cargo oxide run async_mlp` from the cuda-oxide workspace."
msgstr ""
